<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/37607341-jean-hess"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1615496612i/37607341._UX100_CR0,14,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/37607341-jean-hess">Jean Hess</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">At the end he talks about what is needed in the future, like soverienty, although he makes it clear that those things may never happen. Tragic. I also<a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">At the end he talks about what is needed in the future, like soverienty, although he makes it clear that those things may never happen. Tragic. I also like that he emphasizes the paramount influence of land greed on everything that has happened -- everything. He is crystal clear about this especially in the last part of the book. Deconstruct any problem and land emerges as a key determinant. That is to say, for example, any "power imbalance" will ultimately be related to land greed.<a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
