<div id="review_2039561393" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2039561393" />
    <a title="Elyse  Walters" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/597461-elyse-walters"><img alt="Elyse  Walters" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1514246949p2/597461.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2039561393?book_show_action=true">Dec 02, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Elyse  Walters" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Elyse  Walters" href="/user/show/597461-elyse-walters">Elyse  Walters</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2039561393" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1092523154932949014">Thomas King wrote the following at the beginning:<br/>“The Inconvenient Indian” is <br/>fraught with history, underlying narrative is a series of conversations and arguments that I’ve been having with myself and others for most of my adult life, and if there is any methodology in my approach to the subject, it draws more on storytelling techniques than historiography”. <br/><br/>“Any discussion of Indians in North America is likely to conjure at a certain amount of rage. And sorrow. Along with moments of irony and </span>
  <span id="freeText1092523154932949014" style="display:none">Thomas King wrote the following at the beginning:<br />“The Inconvenient Indian” is <br />fraught with history, underlying narrative is a series of conversations and arguments that I’ve been having with myself and others for most of my adult life, and if there is any methodology in my approach to the subject, it draws more on storytelling techniques than historiography”. <br /><br />“Any discussion of Indians in North America is likely to conjure at a certain amount of rage. And sorrow. Along with moments of irony and humor”. <br /><br />When Thomas King was a child, Indians were Indians. “Sometimes Indians were Mohawks, or Cherokees or Crees or Blackfoot or Tlingits or Seminoles. <br />Eventually Indians became Amerindians, and Aboriginals and Indigenous People and American Indians. Lately, Indians have become First Nations in Canada and Native Americans in the United States, but the fact of the matter is that there has never been a good collective noun because there never was a collective to begin with”. <br /><br />My daughter and her husband live in Calgary... ( they sent me this book), and there’s a little town in Alberta north of Jasper called Pocahontas, where you can rent a little cabin with a kitchenette in the heart of nature. Guests can relax, enjoy email at the Poco Cafe - and enjoy their hot springs. <br />I laughed when Thomas King said it was on his bucket list, to visit. I hope he had a chance to stay there. I wouldn’t mind spending a couple of nights there myself. <br /><br />I loved Thomas writing. He made reading about the history intimate. He was often funny... yet he wrote &amp; educated readers about the deeper truths, concerns and issues of native peoples in both Canada and the United States with more stories of substance than the fiction of the Almo massacre and Pocahontas. <br /><br /> “For us Live Indians, being invisible is annoying enough, but being inauthentic is crushing”. <br /><br />Live Indians and Dead Indians came together at powwow ceremonies and art markets from Alberta to Arizona, Oklahoma to Ontario, the Northwest Territories to New Mexico. <br /><br /> “Dead Indians are dignified, noble, silent, suitably garbed. And dead. Live Indians are invisible, unruly, disappointing. And breathing. One is a romantic reminder of a heroic but sectional passed. The other is simply an unpleasant, contemporary surprise”. <br /><br /> ... entertaining, enraging, informative and reflective—<br />The decline and destruction of the Indian tribes was eye opening.<br /><br />Thomas King made no apologies for the history... but rather allowed us, the reader,<br />to experience the impact the culture had pushed aside to justify the compliances with western beliefs. <br /><br />Treaties were made and abrogated in order for the Canadian and US government to easily take the land from Natives. <br /><br />The expression of “Inconvenient Indians” and “Dead Indians” — “Real Indians” and “Legal Indians”, explain how the native peoples were/are perceived by the general population. <br /><br />Packed with history, and humor. <br />King has a wonderful engaging sardonic style of writing, while thoroughly examining the horrific accounts of the European adventures in North America that still unfortunately continue today.<br />White history in North America was shameful. <br /><br />King uncovers the uncomfortable truths — without beating whites over the head — <br />He simply educates with a witty personality.<br /><br />The research was impeccable, and ambitious....<br />This would be a fantastic<br />historical discussion book for high school students in both United States and Canada. <br /><br />Many thanks to my son-in-law, Adam, for sending me this book. <br /><br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="1092523154932949014" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


