    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3411338411" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3411338411" />
    <a title="Christopher" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5961369-christopher"><img alt="Christopher" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1587679195p2/5961369.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3411338411?book_show_action=true">Jun 25, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Christopher" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Christopher" href="/user/show/5961369-christopher">Christopher</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3411338411" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15585539522900584047">It is weird how hard it is to care about the plight of the American Indian. I wonder if this is how Israelis feel about Palestinians and every other dominant group feels about the minority they traditionally abuse. I mean, I want to care. I care about various other peoples who face oppression at the hands of white folks. But why do I feel so little when it comes to these human beings in my own backyard?<br/><br/>This understanding that even most bleeding heart liberals lack the emotional energy to call fo</span>
  <span id="freeText15585539522900584047" style="display:none">It is weird how hard it is to care about the plight of the American Indian. I wonder if this is how Israelis feel about Palestinians and every other dominant group feels about the minority they traditionally abuse. I mean, I want to care. I care about various other peoples who face oppression at the hands of white folks. But why do I feel so little when it comes to these human beings in my own backyard?<br /><br />This understanding that even most bleeding heart liberals lack the emotional energy to call for change permeates this excellent book. My cousins are Native, my classmates were Native. The Natives stage demonstrations not too far from where I live. While nobody I know wishes ill on them, we don't really wish anything on them at all. We just seem to want to forget (and hope that they forget, too, so we can steal more of their land, as King makes clear: No Indian Treaty, he says, has ever not resulted in them losing land.)<br /><br />Just to bolster this claim, I checked Facebook. Out of the 50 most recent posts on a Canadian progressive group, just two (incidentally the 25th and 50th) were about Indigenous issues, and they had like two comments and three likes between them. That's very out of the ordinary compared to what the interactions for most other posts looked like.<br /><br />So if the victims of the greatest genocide in history, a genocide which depopulated almost two entire continents of almost a hundred million people, have a hard time winning the sympathy of a bunch of BDS-activists and leftists, what could they possibly do to win our recognition of their rights from the broader population?<br /><br />The only times I ever hear talk about the "Indians", as most people still say, is when they are demonstrating. Usually it is when they've put up a roadblock. It is not a very uncommon occurrence, I can recall several times it has happened in my short life. Now and then, CBC might have a short piece on murdered indigenous women, but even that only comes up once or twice a year and hardly attracts much spectacle.<br /><br />Perhaps I've been wrong in these observations. There is one other reason why Indian affairs is brought up, and it is the most common: "I think I'm like 1/64th Native, do you think I can get free glasses?" I've always found these discussions quite awkward. To them, their supposed First Nations heritage is nothing but a gimmick to get a handout. This benefit from the Canadian government, and others like it, are all that Nativeness is worth to most people. <br /><br />And yet life goes on. The alcoholism and the suicides, which is pretty much what whites think is their entire way of life, goes on and on, more suffering, more death, all of it needless, none of it arousing the indignation or the spirit of revolution and change that they would if we were talking about any other people. It's all in the periphery, all in the open but over to the side enough that we can pretend we don't see it. <br /><br />My opening observation might be wrong, too. Maybe it isn't so weird after all. We, the White Man, came and butchered and massacred by the thousands. We're worse even than the Nazis, in terms of the scale and thoroughness of our genocide. That's a pretty hard past to reckon with (maybe we should look to Germany and how they make peace with their past?), with the scraggly band of survivors shut up on their reservations as the living reminder of the cruelty we would prefer to pretend is not within us. Our entire dual continent of the Americas has been bathed in the blood of its own children and then the land itself has been transformed into private parcels that we, the interloper, the usurper, the murderer, continue to fight and to kill over. Welcome to America.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15585539522900584047" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


