<div id="review_1571227161" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1571227161" />
    <a title="Lauren " class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1291915-lauren"><img alt="Lauren " src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1643729278p2/1291915.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1571227161?book_show_action=true">Nov 27, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lauren " class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lauren " href="/user/show/1291915-lauren">Lauren </a>
      </span>

          added it


          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780385664226" href="/book/show/17568771-the-inconvenient-indian">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1291915-lauren?shelf=world-history">world-history</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1291915-lauren?shelf=own">own</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1291915-lauren?shelf=canada-canadian-lit">canada-canadian-lit</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1291915-lauren?shelf=rtw21">rtw21</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1291915-lauren?shelf=social-justice-commentary">social-justice-commentary</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1291915-lauren?shelf=us-history">us-history</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1291915-lauren?shelf=indigenous-native-first-nations">indigenous-native-first-nations</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1291915-lauren?shelf=race-racism-antiracism">race-racism-antiracism</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1571227161" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13410120938018375186"><i>&quot;The sad truth is that, within the public sphere, within the collective consciousness of the general populace, most of the history of Indians in North America has been forgotten, and what we are left with is a series of historical artifacts...&quot;</i><br/><br/>From THE INCONVENIENT INDIAN: A Curious Account of Native People in North America by Thomas King, 2012.<br/><br/>The place where I currently live (Maryland, United States) is the ancestral home of the Lenape, Nanticoke, Piscataway, Conoy, Powhatan, Accohannock, Shaw</span>
  <span id="freeText13410120938018375186" style="display:none"><i>"The sad truth is that, within the public sphere, within the collective consciousness of the general populace, most of the history of Indians in North America has been forgotten, and what we are left with is a series of historical artifacts..."</i><br /><br />From THE INCONVENIENT INDIAN: A Curious Account of Native People in North America by Thomas King, 2012.<br /><br />The place where I currently live (Maryland, United States) is the ancestral home of the Lenape, Nanticoke, Piscataway, Conoy, Powhatan, Accohannock, Shawnee, Susquehannock, Tutelo &amp; Saponi tribes, and likely many more. This region has been colonized since the 1600s, and 400+ years on, the few Indigenous reminders around us - as King notes in the quotation above - are historical artifacts, primarily in the form of geographic and political markers - names of rivers, counties, towns, highways, state parks, and road side signs.<br /><br />King notes in his narrative "account" (he's careful not to describe his work as a history per se) that what comes to North American settler mind is a dead "Indian" - past tense.<br /><br />The narrative he constructs spends 300+ pages with a surprisingly comprehensive macrohistory of Turtle Island's millions of Indigenous peoples who are very much STILL HERE.<br /><br />King's style is engaging, folksy, and subversive - but most of all accessible and highly readable. The narrative is structured like an extended conversation with multiple anecdotes, witty commentary &amp; allusions, and notes of what his wife Helen says he should / shouldn't include in the text. The style was reminsicent of Bill Bryson or Teffi in wit, humour, and pathos.<br /><br />📚 Recommended as a starting point - or a reminder text. King is also a novelist and I'm curious to check out his fictional works after reading this one.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13410120938018375186" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

